Fixed issue with single include generator - well, partially. The problem is it is matching /* u00e2u0080u00a6 */ comments by assuming the intervening lines begin with whitespace followed by a *. This avoids it having to maintain extra state, but makes it brittle. It was matching *it =   + *it; as a comment! It now matches on a single space followed by a  * and this seems to work for now - but it probably needs to move to proper stateful comment handling.

build 1.3.0-develop.1I've incremented the minor release number. This is a slight abuse of semantic versioning so let me explain:nI've slightly changed how matchers are used. The matcher macro (REQUIRE_THAT/ CHECK_THAT) used to introduce the Catch::Matchers namespace before the macro token for the matcher, to save you having import the namespace yourself.nThe trouble is if the matcher token is not a simple matcher (can now be an expression) this breaks!nSo I've removed that qualification. Now if you use Matchers you'll have to do somethings like using namespace Catch::Matchers to bring them in.nThis is a breaking change - but, OTTOH, Matchers are an undocumented beta' feature that I've stated in the past is not guaranteed to have a stable API - so I don't think this warrants a major version change - but I did want to make it significant enough that people do notice that something is going on - and perhaps lead them to this commit message.n

Fixes for XML encoding.This commit fixes the following scenario:n  * You have a test that compares strings with embedded controln  characters.n  * The test fails.n  * You are using JUnit tests within TeamCity.nnBefore this commit, the JUnit report watcher fails on parsing the XMLnfor two reasons: the control characters are missing a semicolon at thenend, and the XML document doesn't specify that it is XML 1.1.nnXML 1.0 --- what we get if we don't specify an XML version --- doesn't support embedding control characters --- seenhttp://stackoverflow.com/questions/404107/why-are-control-characters-illegal-in-xmlnfor all of the gory details.nnThis is based on PR #588 by @mrpin

Fix random_shuffle narrowing warningsCatch passes an RNG which accepts int to random_shuffle. Insidenrandom_shuffle, the STL tries to call that RNG with the difference_typenof the user provided iterators. For std::vector, this is ptrdiff_t,nwhich on amd64 builds is wider than int. This triggers a narrowingnwarning because the 64 bit difference is being truncated to 32 bits.nnNote that this RNG implementation still does not produce a correctlynuniformly shuffled result -- it's currently asserting that std::randncan produce 1000000 which is false -- but I don't know enough aboutnhow much repeatable shuffles are necessary here, so I'm leaving thatnalone for now.n

Fix transform narrowing warningsCatch passes ::tolower into std::transform with string iterators.n::tolower has the signature int(int), which triggers a stealth narrowingnwarning inside std::transform, because transform callsn*_Dest = _Fn(*_First), which implicitly narrows an int to a char.nnFor this particular application the narrowing is fine, so explicitlynnarrow in a lambda.n
Fix transform without a lambdaCatch apparently supports targeting C++03, so use an inline functionninstead.n

commit_message: Fixed compile error under VS2015 /c++:latest, caused by using random_shuffleNow if we detect C++11 compiler, or MSVC in version corresponding to VS2015,nwe switch from using `std::random_shuffle` to `std::shuffle`.nn`std::random_shuffle` was officially deprecated in C++14, and removed in C++17.nnAlso removed guarded inclusion of `<random>` header, as there was nothingnin the header that used it.n

Added NOMINMAX and WIN32_LEAN_AND_MEAN defines before including windows.hThis stops the `windows.h` header from defining `min` and `max` macrosnand including lot of Windows APIs that are not needed by Catch.n

Fix for sigsegv stack overflow behaviorAlso stops Catch from assuming its the only signal user in the binary,nand makes it restore the signal handlers it has replaced. Same goes fornthe signal stack.nnThe signal stack itself probably shouldn't be always reallocated fornfragmentation reasons, but that can be fixed later on.n

Added signal handling under Windows.Only some signals are handled under Windows, because Windows does notnuse signals per-se and the mechanics are different. For now, we handlensigsegv, stack overflow, div-by-zero and sigill. We can alsonmeaningfullynadd various floating point errors, but not sigterm and family, becausensigterm is not a structured exception under Windows.nnThere is also no catch-all, because that would also catch variousndebugger-related exceptions, like EXCEPTION_BREAKPOINT.n
Reset signals immediately after use and re-raise orginal signal instead of just exiting
Added single char version of logo
Removed superfluous comments (bad merge after cherry pick).

If we receive a signal, we re-register ALL previous signal handlers.This fixes the case when we pass signal to previously registerednhandler, and it needs to transform the signal into different one.nnStill problematic: What if the signal handler we replaced does notnterminate the application? We can end up in a weird state and loopnforever.nnPossible solution: Deregister our signal handlers, CALL the previousnsignal handler explicitly and if control returns, abort. This wouldnhowever complicate our code quite a bit, as we would have to parse thensigaction we delegate to, decide whether to use signal handler or signalnaction, etc...n
First commit of benchmarks for Catch runtime perf.So far its very much a WIP with some problems that are known already andnnot very representative tests.n

Various small string usage performance improvements.* Empty strings are now direct constructed as `std::string()`, not as empty string literals.n* `startsWith` and `endsWith` no longer construct new a string. This should be an improvementnfor libstdc++ when using older standards, as it doesn't use SSO but COW and thus even shortnstrings are expensive to first create.n* Various places now use char literal instead of string literals containing single char.n** `startsWith` and `endsWith` now also have overload that takes single char.nnGenerally the performance improvements under VS2015 are small, as going from short stringnto char is mostly meaningless because of SSO (Catch doesn't push string handling that hard)nand previous commit removed most string handling if tests pass, which is the expect case.n
Add support for breaking into debugger for LinuxUse Linux-specific /proc/$PID/status file to check whether we're beingndebugged and a generic raise(SIGTRAP) to actually break into the debugger.n

Refactor CATCH_BREAK_INTO_DEBUGGER() to avoid repetitionDon't duplicate Catch::isDebuggerActive() check many times, do it just oncenin CATCH_BREAK_INTO_DEBUGGER() definition and use a separate CATCH_TRAP()nmacro for the really platform-dependent part.n

Use inline assembly with gcc under Linux for CATCH_TRAPThis is more convenient than using the generic portable raise(SIGTRAP) as itnavoids having another stack frame in the debugger when the break happens.n

CATCH_CONFIG_FAST_COMPILE now disables trys in REQUIRE*This seems to give about 15% speedup when compiling tests using GCC.nnThe tradeoff is that under certain circumstances, there is a chance fornfalse negative result, when the expression under test throws exceptionnand the test code catches it before it gets to the test runner.nnExample:n``` cppnTEST_CASE(False negative) {ntry {nREQUIRE(throws() == );n} catch (...) {}n}n```nThis test case will succeed, reporting no assertions checked, instead ofnfailing as it would with `CATCH_CONFIG_FAST_COMPILE` disabled. However,njust removing the try-catch block inside client's code will fix this, sonit is worthwhile.nnThis change does not apply to CHECK* macros, because these are currentlynspecified as continuing on exception and thus need the local try-catchnto work as intended.n

Added templated constructor to C++11 ApproxWhen using C++11, comparison operators are already templated to takenanything that can be explicitly converted to double, but constructorntook only doubles. This lead to warnings when an `Approx` wasnconstructed from floats, which was problematic for some users.nnSince just adding float constructor would be a large breaking change, asnsuddenly `Approx( 1 )` would become ambiguous, I added a templatednconstructor that will take anything that is explicitly convertible tondouble. This has the added benefit of allowing constructing `Approx`ninstances from instances of strong typedefs, ie allowingn`calculated_temp == Approx( known_temp)`.nnCloses #873n

Don't include warning headers from catch_xmlwriter.hppThis prevents Catch from disabling `Wpadded` for Clang inside test filesn(files that do not define either `CATCH_CONFIG_MAIN` orn`CATCH_CONFIG_RUNNER`).nncatch_suppress_warnings.h and catch_reenable_warnings.h should benincluded only once*, so that the stitching script includes them as thenfirst and last header respectively, since it only includes each headernonce. Approx rework: default scale == 0, epsilon applies to Approx::valueAlso adds check to Approx::epsilon that the new epsilon has a validn(ie one between 0 and 1)nnBased onnhttp://realtimecollisiondetection.net/blog/?p=89nhttps://randomascii.wordpress.com/2012/02/25/comparing-floating-point-numbers-2012-edition/nhttps://docs.oracle.com/cd/E19957-01/806-3568/ncg_goldberg.htmlnhttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Approximation_error#Formal_DefinitionnnThe given epsilon should refer to the target value, otherwisenthe result would be unexpected, e.g. 101.02 == Approx(100).epsilon(0.01)nis true.nThe default scale should be invisible, thus,ne.g. 101.01 == Approx(100).epsilon(0.01) gets false.nFinally even 101.000001 == Approx(100).epsilon(0.01) is falsen

Add an experimental new way of capturing stdout/stderrUnlike the relatively non-invasive old way of capturing stdout/stderr,nthis new way is also able to capture output from C's stdlib functionsnsuch as `printf`. This is done by redirecting stdout and stderr filendescriptors to a file, and then reading this file back.nnThis approach has two sizeable drawbacks:n1) Performance, obviously. Previously an installed capture made thenprogram run faster (as long as it was then discarded), because a callnto `std::cout` did not result in text output to the console. This newncapture method in fact forces disk IO. While it is likely that anynmodern OS will keep this file in memory-cache and might never actuallynissue the IO to the backing storage, it is still a possibility andncalls to the file system are not free.nn2) Nonportability. While POSIX is usually assumed portable, and thisnimplementation relies only on a very common parts of it, it is nonlonger standard C++ (or just plain C) and thus might not be availablenon some obscure platforms. Different C libs might also implement thenrelevant functions in a less-than-useful ways (e.g. MS's `tmpfile`ngenerates a temp file inside system folder, so it will not worknwithout elevated privileges and thus is useless).nnThese two drawbacks mean that, at least for now, the new capture isnopt-in. To opt-in, `CATCH_CONFIG_EXPERIMENTAL_REDIRECT` needs to bendefined in the implementation file.nnCloses #1243n

Fix VS2017 approvals on AppVeyorBecause of a change in VS toolset, missing option <UseFullPaths>nis no longer interpreted as don't pass /FC to the compiler, butnrather as pass /FC to the compiler. Add support for -fno-exceptions (or equivalent)This meansnn* Adding new configuration toggle `CATCH_CONFIG_DISABLE_EXCEPTIONS`nand a best-guess configuration auto-checking for it.n* Adding new set of internal macros, `CATCH_TRY`, `CATCH_CATCH_ALL`nand `CATCH_CATCH_ANON` that can be used in place of regular `try`,n`catch(...)` and `catch(T const&)` respectively, while disappearingnwhen `CATCH_CONFIG_DISABLE_EXCEPTIONS` is enabled.n* Replacing all uses of `throw` with calls to `Catch::throw_exception`ncustomization point.n* Providing a default implementation for the above customization pointnwhen `CATCH_CONFIG_DISABLE_EXCEPTIONS` is set.n* Letting users override this implementation with their own.n* Some minor changes and ifdefs all around to support the aboven

Integrate Nonius benchmark into Catch2Changes done to Nonius:n* Moved things into Catch::Benchmark namespacen* Benchmarks were integrated with `TEST_CASE`/`SECTION`/`GENERATE` macrosn* Removed Nonius's parameters for benchmarks, Generators should be used insteadn* Added relevant methods to the reporter interface (default-implemented, to avoidnbreaking existing 3rd party reporters)n* Async processing is guarded with `_REENTRANT` macro for GCC/Clang, used by defaultnon MSVCn* Added a macro `CATCH_CONFIG_DISABLE_BENCHMARKING` that removes all traces ofnbenchmarking from Catchn

Various improvements to the benchmarking support* Units from <ratio> are no longer redeclared in our own namespacen* The default clock is `steady_clock`, not `high_resolution_clock`,nbecause, as HH says high_resolution_clock is useless. If you wantnmeasure the passing of time, use steady_clock. If you want usernfriendly time, use system_clock.n* Benchmarking support is opt-in, not opt-out, to avoid the largen(~10%) compile time penalty.n* Benchmarking-related options in CLI are always present, to decreasenthe amount of code that is only compiled conditionally and makingnthe whole shebang more maintainble.n

Remove explicit setting of CXX_STANDARD for SelfTest target  - The current setup tries to detect USE_CPP14/USE_CPP17 and sets thenCXX_STANDARD property for the SelfTest target. This is not ideal, sincenCMAKE_CXX_STANDARD can be provided by the toolchain file or as command linenoption and should be used by the library internally correctly.  Hence, thenwhole set of the relevant lines from `projects/CMakeLists.txt` have beennremoved.nn  - The above can also cause subtle issues where the user is expecting the testsnto compile with C++17 after setting CMAKE_CXX_STANDARD and then gettingnresults of compilation with C++11 as USE_CPP17 has not been set.nn  - The current build matrix used the above code to run the tests. So, evennthough the it should not required anymore to build Catch2, it was stillnrequired to send correct options to build matrix. In that respect,n.travis.yml has been modified to send correct options to the build commandnin the new setup.n

Rework StringRef interface and internalsNow it no longer tries to be this weird hybrid between an owningnand non-owning reference, and is only ever non-owning. This is alsonreflected in its interface, for example `StringRef::isNullTerminated`nis now public, and `StringRef::c_str()` has the precondition that itnis true.nnOverview of the changes:n* The `StringRef::m_data` member has been completely removed, as itnhad no more uses.n* `StringRef::isSubstring()` has been made public and renamed ton`StringRef::isNullTerminated()`, so that the name reflects what thenmethod actually does.n* `StringRef::currentData()` has been renamed to `StringRef::data()`,nto be in line with common C++ containers and container-alikes.n* `StringRef::c_str()` will no longer silently make copies. It insteadnhas a precondition that `isNullTerminated()` is true.n* If the user needs a null-terminated string, they should use then`std::string` conversion operator and call `c_str()` on the resultingn`std::string`.n* Some small optimizations in various places.n* Basic functionality is now `constexpr`.n

Rework how warning suppression in macros is donePreviously, each warning suppression was self-contained, with itsnown pair of `SUPPRESS_X_WARNING` and `UNSUPPRESS_X_WARNING` macros.nThis had the obvious advantage of being self-containing, but itnalso meant that if we needed to suppress more than one warningnin a single place, then we would manipulate the compiler's warningnstate multiple times, even though logically we would only need onenlayer.nnThe new way of suppressing warnings in macros is to push compiler'snwarning state with `CATCH_INTERNAL_START_WARNINGS_SUPPRESSION` macro,nthen disable whatever macros we need with then`CATCH_INTERNAL_SUPPRESS_X_WARNINGS` macro, and then return to thenprevious state using `CATCH_INTERNAL_STOP_WARNINGS_SUPPRESSION`.n
